The error you're encountering is due to using the Fetch API incorrectly. In Node.js environments, the `fetch` function doesn't return a Response object with a `.json()` method directly. Instead, you need to use the `body` property of the response and parse it manually.

Here's how to fix your code:

```javascript
const getMovieList = async () => {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('https://api.themoviedb.org/3/movie/popular?api_key=YOUR_API_KEY');

    // Check if response is ok
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }

    // Parse the JSON manually
    const data = await response.text();
    const jsonData = JSON.parse(data);

    return jsonData.results;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching movie list:', error);
    throw error;
  }
};
```

Alternatively, if you're using a library like `node-fetch`, you would need to import it properly:

```javascript
const fetch = require('node-fetch');

const getMovieList = async () => {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('https://api.themoviedb.org/3/movie/popular?api_key=YOUR_API_KEY');
    const data = await response.json(); // This will work with node-fetch
    return data.results;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching movie list:', error);
    throw error;
  }
};
```

The key issue is that in standard Node.js environments, the global `fetch` function doesn't behave the same way as in browsers.

