Here's a Java Spark solution for SCD Type 2 implementation without UDFs, with parametrizable fields and hashing:

```java
import org.apache.spark.sql.*;
import org.apache.spark.sql.functions.*;
import org.apache.spark.sql.types.*;

public class SCD2Spark {
    public static Dataset<Row> generateSCD2(Dataset<Row> currentData, Dataset<Row> newData, String[] keyFields, String[] attributeFields, String hashField, String effectiveDateField, String expiryDateField) {
        // Hash the attribute fields
        Dataset<Row> hashedNewData = hashAttributes(newData, attributeFields, hashField);

        // Add effective date to new data
        Dataset<Row> newDataWithDates = hashedNewData.withColumn(effectiveDateField, current_date())
                                                   .withColumn(expiryDateField, lit(null).cast(DataTypes.StringType));

        // Join with current data on key fields
        Dataset<Row> joinCondition = concat(currentData.col(keyFields[0]), currentData.col(keyFields[1]))
                                    .equalTo(concat(newDataWithDates.col(keyFields[0]), newDataWithDates.col(keyFields[1])));

        Dataset<Row> joinedData = currentData.join(newDataWithDates, joinCondition, "left_outer");

        // Identify records that have changed
        Dataset<Row> changedRecords = joinedData.filter(col(hashField + "_new").notEqual(col(hashField + "_old"))
                                                  .or(col(hashField + "_old").isNull()));

        // Update expiry dates for changed records
        Dataset<Row> updatedExpiryDates = changedRecords.withColumn(expiryDateField, current_date());

        // Prepare new records (insert)
        Dataset<Row> newRecords = newDataWithDates.filter(col(hashField + "_new").notEqual(col(hashField + "_old"))
                                                      .or(col(hashField + "_old").isNull()))
                                                 .withColumn(expiryDateField, lit(null).cast(DataTypes.StringType));

        // Combine updated and new records
        Dataset<Row> result = updatedExpiryDates.union(newRecords);

        return result;
    }

    private static Dataset<Row> hashAttributes(Dataset<Row> data, String[] attributeFields, String hashField) {
        // Concatenate attribute fields
        Column concatenated = concat_ws("|", 
            java.util.Arrays.stream(attributeFields)
                           .map(data::col)
                           .toArray(Column[]::new));

        // Hash the concatenated string
        Dataset<Row> hashedData = data.withColumn(hashField, hash(concatenated));

        return hashedData;
    }
}
```

This implementation:
1. Takes current and new data as inputs
2. Accepts arrays of key fields and attribute fields
3. Uses hashing to detect changes in attributes
4. Handles SCD Type 2 logic with effective and expiry dates
5. Does not use UDFs
6. Is parametrizable through field names

To use this code:
1. Call `generateSCD2()` with your datasets
2. Provide arrays of key fields and attribute fields
3. Specify field names for effective date, expiry date, and hash

