To limit Laravel routes to 400 executions per second across all users, you'll need to implement a global rate limiter. Here's how to do it:

1. First, create a custom rate limiter in your RouteServiceProvider or via a middleware:

```php
// In app/Http/Kernel.php, add to $middlewareGroups
protected $middlewareGroups = [
    'web' => [
        // ... other middleware
        \App\Http\Middleware\GlobalRateLimit::class,
    ],
];
```

2. Create the middleware:

```php
// app/Http/Middleware/GlobalRateLimit.php
<?php

namespace App\Http\Middleware;

class GlobalRateLimit
{
    public function handle($request, $next)
    {
        static $lastReset = 0;
        static $count = 0;

        $currentTime = microtime(true);

        // Reset counter every second
        if ($currentTime - $lastReset >= 1) {
            $lastReset = $currentTime;
            $count = 0;
        }

        // Check if we're under the limit
        if ($count >= 400) {
            return response('Too Many Requests', 429);
        }

        $count++;

        return $next($request);
    }
}
```

3. Alternative approach using Laravel's built-in rate limiting with a custom limiter:

```php
// In app/Http/Kernel.php
protected $routeMiddleware = [
    // ... other middleware
    'global.rate.limit' => \App\Http\Middleware\GlobalRateLimit::class,
];
```

4. Apply to specific routes:

```php
Route::middleware(['global.rate.limit'])->group(function () {
    Route::get('/api/endpoint', [YourController::class, 'handle']);
});
```

This approach ensures that the 400 requests per second limit is enforced globally across all users, not individually.

